article.headline: Jaw wired shut, Williams comes through
article.linkText: Illinois overcomes Illinois State in OT
article.story: CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Deron Williams, playing with his jaw wired shut, scored 20 points and Illinois (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) recovered from an 11-point deficit to beat Illinois State 80-73 in overtime Saturday. The Illini needed all the help they could get from a sellout crowd of 16,500 during the comeback, which started with Nick Smith's dunk with 7:33 left in the second half. The Illini outscored ISU 19-10 from there, with Williams connecting for 10 points, and Smith's two free throws tied it at 68 at the end of regulation. Illinois (9-2) hit its free throws in the extra period to earn its 22nd straight victory at Assembly Hall. Williams, who missed three games after breaking his jaw in a collision with a Maryland-Eastern Shore player on Dec. 11, entered the game with 13:39 to go in the first half and wound up playing 34 minutes. He hit four 3-pointers, grabbed three rebounds and had three assists. Illinois State was led by Marcus Arnold, who got the better of Illinois' big men all afternoon and scored 23 points. Trey Guidry scored 16 and Gregg Alexander had 14 for the Redbirds (4-6). Dee Brown scored 16 points, Luther Head had 15 and Smith 14 for the Illini. The Redbirds gave the Illini all they could handle, even after the Illini recovered from a 10-point first-half deficit. Illinois State kept its cool late in the first half while the Illini mounted a 10-2 run and swapped baskets in the final minutes, ending the half in a 32-32 tie. The Redbirds came out after the break and regained everything they had lost at the end of the first half. Illinois State took a 52-41 lead when Guidry hit a 3-pointer with about 12 minutes to go. Smith's dunk and Williams' 3-pointer brought the Illini within four, but Guidry hit another 3 and Arnold scored from inside to stop Illinois' run. From there, it was all Illinois. The Illini smothered ISU defensively, forcing poor shots and three turnovers down the stretch. Williams converted two of those into Illinois points. Illinois State jumped out to a 10-point lead early and it took most of the first half for the Illini to recover. Roger Powell's dunk with 8:30 left sparked a 12-2 run, and Williams' basket four minutes later gave Illinois its first lead at 26-25. Williams hit two 3-pointers in the final 3:30 of the half. The game was tied seven times and there were seven lead changes.
